:"1332","about 1348":"circa 1348","1375":"1375","1308":"1308","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Cedigra, Montgomercyshire, Wales":"Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Llanuwchllyn, Merionethshire, Wales":"Llanuwchllyn, Merionethshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Breconshire, Wales":"Breconshire, Wales","{Rhys ap Tewdwr}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Italië"},"en":{"1302–":"1302–Deceased","1302–Male":"1302–Deceased","1308–Female":"1308–Deceased","1332–1375":"1332–1375","1348–Male":"1348–Deceased","1350–1447":"from9January1350to8January1351–1447","1352–Male":"1352–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1279–1355":"1279–1355","1283–Female":"1283–Deceased","about 1360":"about 1360","1352":"1352","1350":"from 9 January 1350 to 8 January 1351","1283":"1283","1447":"1447","1348":"1348","1302":"1302","1279":"1279","1355":"1355","1332":"1332","about 1348":"about 1348","1375":"1375","1308":"1308","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, United Kingdom","Cedigra, Montgomercyshire, Wales":"Wales, United Kingdom","Llanuwchllyn, Merionethshire, Wales":"Llanuwchllyn, Merionethshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Breconshire, Wales":"Breconshire, Wales","{Rhys ap Tewdwr}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Italy","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Dutch: occupational name for a cobbler.","Slovenian: nickname for a talkative person, from <i>lapati</i> ‘to babble’, or a topographic name from dialect <i>lap</i> ‘abyss’. Compare   Lapp   4."],"variants":[{"name":"Lapp","meanings":["German, English, and Dutch: from Middle High German and Middle English <i>lappe</i>, Middle Dutch <i>lap</i> ‘cloth, patch, rag’, a metonymic occupational name for a mender of clothes or shoes, or a nickname given to someone who wore ragged clothes or garments with loose folds, flaps, or hanging sleeves, or who had fleshy folds of skin on his face, neck, or body.","German: nickname for a simple-minded person, from Middle Low German <i>lappe</i> ‘fool’. This surname (in any of the two possible senses; see also 1 above) is also found in France (mainly Alsace, also Lorraine).","English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>lappe</i> ‘burdock’, perhaps for someone with a prickly character."]}]},{"name":"llywellen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Welsh:  see  Llewellyn  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Llewellyn","meanings":["Welsh: from the personal name <i>Llywelyn</i>, derived from British Celtic <i>Lugubelinos</i>, itself from the divine name <i>Lugus</i> + an uncertain second element often used alone as a name. Through association with <i>llew</i> ‘lion’, it was altered to <i>Llewelyn</i>. This was the name of two princes of north Wales who held the Normans at bay for many years in the 13th century. Etymologically speaking, the form with a fourth <i>-l-</i> is an error, not found as an original Welsh name, but this is now much the most common spelling in the US."]}]},{"name":"Ieuan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Iefan","meanings":["Later form of   Ieuan ."]},{"name":"Ifan","meanings":["From Latin <i>Iohannes</i>.  See  <b>John</b>   ."]},{"name":"John","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ieuan Ap llywellen was born in 1302, in Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Gwilym Ap Llewelyn, was 24 and his mother, Gwladys verch Philip, was 20. He married Meddefus verch Gruffydd in 1327, in Caernarfonshire, Wales, United Kingdom. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1302–":"1302–Surnud","1302–Male":"1